         <div type="traslation">
            <head>Translation</head>
              <lg>
               <l> In the [Jovian year] called Saumya and also in autumn, when the [month] of
                  Vṛścika breaks forth, in the sixth [lunar day] in the bright fortnight, in the day
                  of the week which bears the name of the [Jovian] year <note n="1">i.e. Saumya,
                     corresponding to Wednesday</note>, in the constellation devoted to Viṣṇu <note
                     n="2"><foreign xml:lang="san-Latn">bhe vaiṣṇave</foreign>, i.e. Śrāvaṇa; also,
                     through <foreign xml:lang="san-Latn">śleṣa</foreign>: staying in the splendour
                     of Viṣṇu</note> as he were in his own Sarvādvaita doctrine, Śrīnivāsa – that
                  follower of the Sāman [branch of the Veda] who bears an auspicious name<note n="3">
                     <foreign xml:lang="san-Latn">saunāmā</foreign>, probably because Śrīnivāsa is
                     also a name of Viṣṇu</note> – copied here the manuscript<note n="4">pustukaṃ
                     [sic!]</note> of the <foreign xml:lang="san-Latn">ṛcas</foreign>. May the good
                  ones forgive the mistake made by [my] hand.</l>
            </lg>
         </div>
